1) Read the data description on DMR p.297. Identify and report response variable and predictors.Â¶

>It has two response variables RISK_Adjustment and TARGET_Adjusted. RISK_Adjustment is a continuous variable, and TARGET_Adjusted is a binary variable which is consisted of 1 and 0.

>The other variables such as Age, Employment, Education, Marital, Occupation, Income, Gender, Deductions, and Hours are predictors.

>ID is a unique identifier for each record, so it's not considered as a predictor.

In [11]:
ggplot(ad, aes(x=Hours)) + geom_density() +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks=round(seq(0, max(ad$Hours), by=10), 1)) + # Changed X axis interval to see its peak value
    geom_vline(xintercept = median(ad$Hours), size = 1, color = 'red', linetype='dashed')

>Based on the density distribution, Hours is a multimodal distribution. It is approximately symmetric at its median 40 (although, it should be mean instead of median by definition). >However, its values are integers(not continuous numbers), and density distribution in this case can somewhat misrepresent its distribution. It's because density function works less well with discrete values than continuous ones.

ggplot(ad, aes(x=RISK_Adjustment)) + geom_density() +

> Based on the density distribution, RISK_Adjustment is a right skewed unimodal distribution with a thin tail. If you exclude the ten outlier values which is greater than 90000, the skewness is not that high.

#### train model1
# predictors: Age+Education+Marital+Occupation+Income+Gender+Deductions+Hours+Employment
model = train(TARGET_Adjusted~Age+Education+Marital+Occupation+Income+Gender+Deductions+Hours+Employment,
              data=ad,method='glm',family=binomial(link='logit'),trControl=trainControl(
                method="cv",number=10,savePredictions = TRUE,classProbs=TRUE))

Warning message:
"glm.fit: fitted probabilities numerically 0 or 1 occurred"
In [21]:
#### model evaluation
# confusionMatrix
cm = table(model$pred$obs,model$pred$pred)
print("Confusion Matrix:")
cm
# calcute the accuracy,precision,recall,F1 value
accuracy = (cm[1,1]+cm[2,2])/(cm[1,1]+cm[1,2]+cm[2,1]+cm[2,2])
precision = cm[1,1]/(cm[1,1]+cm[2,1])
recall = cm[1,1]/(cm[1,1]+cm[1,2])
f1score = 2*precision*recall/(precision+recall)
# AUC
truevalue=data.frame(model$pred$obs)
levels(truevalue$model.pred.obs)=c(0,1)
# use pROC package to calculate AUC value
auc = auc(roc(truevalue$model.pred.obs,model$pred$zero))

#print
cat(sprintf("-----------------------------------------------------\n Accuracy: %f\n Precision: %f\n Recall: %f\n F1: %f\n AUC: %f\n-----------------------------------------------------\n",
            accuracy,precision,recall,f1score,auc))

#plot ROC Curve
plot(roc(truevalue$model.pred.obs,model$pred$zero),main='ROC Curve')

n = length(ad$RISK_Adjustment)
error = dim(n)
formula = RISK_Adjustment ~ Age + Employment + Education + Marital + Deductions + Hours
for (k in 1:n)
{
  train1 = c(1:n)
  train = train1[train1 != k]
  m2 = lm(formula, data = ad[train, ])
  pred = predict(m2, newdata = ad[-train, ]) 
  obs = ad$RISK_Adjustment[-train]
  error[k] = obs - pred
}

# 10-fold cross-validation
n = length(ad$RISK_Adjustment)
error = dim(10)
formula = RISK_Adjustment ~ Employment + Education + Marital + poly(Age, degree = 4) + poly(Deductions, degree = 3)
for (k in 1:10)
{
  test = c(floor((k-1)*n/10+1):floor((k*n/10)))
  train = c(1:n)[-test]
  m2 = lm(formula, data = ad[train, ])
  pred = predict(m2, newdata = ad[test, ]) 
  obs = ad$RISK_Adjustment[test]
  error[k] = sqrt(mean((obs - pred)^2))
}
rmse_poly = sqrt(mean(error^2))
rmse_poly
8004.78311842694

> Therefore, polynomial regression is as bad as the linear regression for this data set.

> [Linear] R-squares(linear) =0.07813 RMSE = 8006.82

> [Poly] R-squares(poly) = 0.08363 RMSE = 8004.78

> Although low R-square values don't always mean bad performance, yet in this case it's really bad, since the R-squares are pretty low for both of the regression models. Actually, the RMSE (around 8000) is higher than a considerable part of the data, which can cause an error larger than 100%. The reason for this is that most of the amount of RISK_Adjustment is zero, which is a very bad condition for numerical regression.
